      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when the temp changes, does that actually shift the balance of which ones are more dominant, or do they just both speed up or slow down? also how does the actual breakdown of the starches into those sugars work? like what's the enzyme part of that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the temperature changes, it can indeed shift the balance of dominance between yeast and lactobacilli in your sourdough starter. At warmer temperatures, yeast tends to dominate, producing more carbon dioxide and causing the dough to rise more quickly. Conversely, at cooler temperatures, lactobacilli become more active, producing more lactic acid and contributing to the sour flavor.\n\nHowever, it's not a simple on/off switch; both yeast and lactobacilli can adapt to changing temperatures by altering their metabolic rates. This is known as \"temperature adaptation\" or \"thermogenic regulation.\" For example, yeast can increase its metabolic rate to produce more enzymes and proteins at warmer temperatures, while lactobacilli can slow down their metabolism to conserve energy at cooler temperatures.\n\nNow, regarding the breakdown of starches into sugars, it's a multi-step process involving several enzymes. The primary enzyme responsible for breaking down starches is amylase, which is produced by both yeast and lactobacilli. Amylase cleaves the alpha-1,4-glycosidic bonds in starch molecules, producing maltose (a disaccharide) and other simpler sugars.\n\nThe maltose is then further broken down into glucose by another",
      "source": "target",
